People use everything backwards, and it's madness.

23
00:01:14,019 --> 00:01:17,439
Usability testing is now an important and kind of accepted

24
00:01:17,519 --> 00:01:18,900
part of development process.

25
00:01:19,360 --> 00:01:21,740
And what analytics does is allows designers

26
00:01:21,780 --> 00:01:23,401
to do that on a mass level.

27
00:01:24,021 --> 00:01:26,961
So every game designer has intuition

28
00:01:27,122 --> 00:01:28,502
about what players will do.

29
00:01:28,842 --> 00:01:31,042
But there's nothing like actual behavior

30
00:01:31,062 --> 00:01:32,923
to tell you what's really going on.

31
00:01:33,443 --> 00:01:35,363
What levels do players get stuck on?

32
00:01:35,523 --> 00:01:37,164
What are their favorite characters to use?

33
00:01:37,224 --> 00:01:37,844
Things like that.

34
00:01:38,504 --> 00:01:40,605
And the best way to get answers to those questions

35
00:01:40,725 --> 00:01:43,225
is to see what players are actually doing.

36
00:01:44,186 --> 00:01:48,367
There's a lot to learn from these methods that you just can't get from any other source,

37
00:01:48,888 --> 00:01:53,770
whether that's a direct answer to something like what weapon is more popular or more effective,

38
00:01:54,230 --> 00:02:00,553
or importantly, just using data trends to find red flags that indicate where you should

39
00:02:00,593 --> 00:02:02,193
spend more of your time investigating.

40
00:02:02,873 --> 00:02:07,255
Either way, it's vital information that you're just ignoring if you don't take advantage

41
00:02:07,295 --> 00:02:08,096
of it as a designer.

42
